Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: My motivation stems from a critical yet underexplored gap in emotion-aware AI systems: the disconnect between what writers *intend* to express emotionally and what readers *actually perceive*. While existing work in empathetic dialogue (Paper 1) focuses on bidirectional emotional alignment between interlocutors, it assumes that emotional expression is transparent and directly interpretable. Similarly, multimodal emotion recognition models like COGMEN (Paper 2) excel at detecting perceived emotions but do not disentangle them from intended ones. Meanwhile, multi-emotion generation frameworks (Paper 3) enable richer emotional outputs but lack mechanisms to evaluate whether the generated emotion matches user intent. This reveals a fundamental misalignment—current models optimize for either expression or perception, but rarely model the *transmission fidelity* of emotion in text. My idea introduces a dual-perspective annotation framework that explicitly captures both writer-intended and reader-perceived emotions across diverse contexts, intensities, and demographic variables. By modeling this "emotional transmission gap," we can train AI systems that are not only expressive but also *emotionally intelligible*, adapting their language based on predicted perceptual variance. This differs from prior work by shifting focus from unidirectional empathy or recognition to *diagnostic modeling of emotional miscommunication*, enabling more human-aligned AI. The novelty lies in systematic human experiments designed to quantify this gap, coupled with a computational framework that learns to minimize it.

